    "These algorithms train on labelled or supervised data, wherein initial studies of normal and intrusive behavior are made.",
    "As soon as learning is complete, they can differentiate between the input data instances as typical and atypical with practical rates of accuracy (Ali 2024).",
    "Nevertheless, the process of acquiring high-quality, labelled data is difficult and takes time, reducing the efficacy of the supervised approaches significantly (Ratner et al. 2016).",
    "Some examples of 'other' categories of algorithms include unsupervised learning algorithms, clustering, e.g., center-based methods (k-means, Density-Based Spatial Clustering Application with Noise (DBSCAN)), and density-based methods.",
    "Density-based methods tend to detect clusters as regions of high density separated by regions of low density."
